The picture thus suggested is that of a candidate 111 the cumbrous whitened toga, pressed by his attendant to hurry across the street in order to shake hands with an influential elector on the path opposite. The street was usually narrow, in Pompeii never more than about 24 feet broad, and often only 9 or 10, inclusive of the paths (maryines), but the latter were as a rule much raised.
